# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: criticisms-of-cargill
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The **1971 Iraq poison grain disaster** was a mass methylmercury poisoning incident where seed grain treated with a methylmercury fungicide, which was never intended for human consumption, was imported into Iraq from Mexico and the United States.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Due to factors like foreign-language labeling and distribution too late into the growing cycle, this toxic grain was consumed as food by Iraqi residents in rural areas of the country.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Sufferers experienced paresthesia (numbness of skin), ataxia (lack of coordination of muscle movements) and vision loss, symptoms similar to those observed in Minamata disease-affected Japan.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Though the official death toll was 459, figures of as much as ten times greater have been suggested.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] When it occurred in 1971, the poisoning was the largest mercury poisoning event in history, with cases peaking in February 1972 and stopping by the end of March.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Reports after the disaster recommended tighter regulation, better labelling and handling of mercury-treated grain, and wider involvement of the World Health Organization in monitoring and preventing poisoning incidents.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Investigation confirmed the particular danger posed to fetuses and young children.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The properties of mercury make it an effective fungicide.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Methylmercury had been banned in Sweden in 1966, the first country to do so, and the United Kingdom followed in 1971.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Previous mercury-poisoning incidents had occurred in Iraq in 1956 and 1960.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] In 1956, there had been around 200 cases, and 70 deaths; in 1960 there had been 1000 cases and 200 deaths, in both cases due to ethylmercury compounds.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Among the recommendations made after the 1960 incident had been to colour any toxic grain for easy identification.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Before the 1971 incident, around 200–300 cases of methylmercury poisoning had been reported worldwide.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Drought had reduced harvests in 1969, affecting 500,000 people, and in 1970.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Some 95,000 tonnes (93,000 long tons; 105,000 short tons) of grain (73,202 tonnes of wheat grain and 22,262 tonnes of barley), coloured a pink-orange hue, were shipped to Iraq from the United States and Mexico.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The wheat arrived in Basra on SS *Trade Carrier* between 16 September and 15 October, the barley between 22 October and 24 November 1971.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Iraq's government chose Mexipak, a high-yield wheat seed developed in Mexico by Norman Borlaug.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The seeds contained an average of 7.9 μg/g of mercury, with some samples containing up to nearly twice that.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The three northern governorates of Nineveh, Kirkuk and Erbil received more than half the shipments.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Contributing factors to the epidemic included the fact that distribution started late, and much grain arrived after the October–November planting season.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Farmers were supposed to plant the poisoned grain, but many instead offered it to their families as food, since their own planting had been completed.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Distribution was, in later stages hurried and open, with grain being distributed free of charge with the expectation of payment in kind when the harvest season came.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Some farmers even sold off their own grain, in order to claim more of the imported grain.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] This left them dependent on tainted grain for the winter.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Many Iraqis were either unaware of the significant health risk posed, or chose to ignore the warnings.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Initially, farmers were to certify with a thumbprint or signature that they understood the grain was poison, however some distributors ignored this requirement.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Warnings on the sacks were in Spanish and English, not at all understood, or included the black-and-white skull and crossbones design, which meant nothing to Iraqis.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The long, asymptomatic latent period of mercury poisoning may have granted farmers a false sense of security when animals fed the grain initially appeared to be fine.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The red dye washed off the grain; the mercury did not.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Hence, washing may have given only the appearance of removing the poison.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The Iraqi government made limited attempts to control the distribution of the mercury grain.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Four high ranking officials were posted at the Basra docks during the first two weeks of unloading.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] However, control of the unloading process slipped afterwards, with some spilt grain being stolen by dockworkers.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Aircraft were used to drop half a million leaflets warning of the mercury, however this was an insufficient quantity for the population at the time.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Ground seed dust inhalation was a contributing factor in farmers during sowing and grinding.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Consumption of ground grain in homemade bread is thought to have been the major source of toxicity, since no cases were reported in urban areas, where government flour supplies were commercially regulated.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The effect of mercury took some time – the latent period between ingestion and the first symptoms (typically paresthesia – numbness in the extremities) was between 16 and 38 days.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Paresthesia was the predominant symptom in less serious cases.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Worse cases included ataxia (typically loss of balance), blindness or reduced vision, and death resulting from central nervous system failure.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Anywhere between 20 and 40 mg of mercury has been suggested as sufficient for paresthesia (between 0.5 and 0.8 mg/kg of body weight).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] On average, individuals affected consumed 20 kg or so of bread; the 73,000 tonnes provided would have been sufficient for over 3 million cases.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The hospital in Kirkuk received large numbers of patients with symptoms that doctors recognised from the 1960 outbreak.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The first case of alkylmercury poisoning was admitted to hospital on 21 December.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] By 26 December, the hospital had issued a specific warning to the government.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] By January 1972, the government had started to strongly warn the populace against eating the grain, although dispatches did not mention the large numbers already ill.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The Iraqi Army soon ordered disposal of the grain and eventually declared anyone found selling it would receive the death penalty.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Farmers dumped their supplies wherever possible, contaminating the water supply (particularly the Tigris).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The government initiated a news blackout and released little information about the outbreak.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The World Health Organization assisted the Iraqi government through the supply of drugs, analytical equipment and expertise.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Many new treatments were tried, since existing methods for heavy metal poisoning were not particularly effective.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Dimercaprol was administered to several patients, but caused rapid deterioration of their condition.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] It was ruled out as a treatment for this sort of poisoning following the outbreak.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Polythiol resins, penicillamine and dimercaprol sulfonate all helped, but are believed to have been largely insignificant in overall recovery and outcomes.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Dialysis was tested on a few patients late in the treatment period, but they showed no clinical improvement.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The result of all treatments was varied, with some patients' blood mercury level being dramatically reduced, but a negligible effect in others.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] All patients received periods of treatment interspersed with lay periods; continuous treatment was suggested in future cases.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Later treatment was less effective in reducing blood toxicity.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] 6,530 patients were admitted to hospitals with poisoning, and 459 deaths were reported.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Cases reached a peak of hundreds per day in January, and had largely subsided by the beginning of March.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Admissions represented every age and gender stratum, although those under the age of ten represented a third of admitted cases.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] This number is "certainly an underestimate", because of the availability of hospital treatment, hospital overcrowding and lack of faith in treatment.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] In the most severely affected areas, prevalence was 28% and mortality was 21% of the cases.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Some Iraqi doctors believe both the number of cases and fatalities are at least ten times too low, with perhaps 100,000 cases of brain damage.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] One suggested reason for the vast discrepancy between reported and estimated numbers of deaths is the Iraqi custom, common to large parts of the Middle East, for a person to die at home when possible.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Home deaths would not have been recorded.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] A large number of patients with minor symptoms recovered completely; those with more serious symptoms improved.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] This was in contrast to expected outcomes, largely based on analysis of Minamata disease in Japan.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] In boys with mercury levels below clinical poisoning, a reduction in school performance was noted, although this correlation could not be confirmed.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] In infants, the mercury poisoning caused central nervous system damage.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Relatively low doses caused slower development in children, and abnormal reflexes.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Different treatments for mercury poisoning have since been developed, and "quiet baby syndrome", characterised by a baby who never cries, is now a recognised symptom of methylmercury-induced brain damage.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Ongoing recommendations of the food regulation authorities have focused on consumption by pregnant women and infant children, noting the particular susceptibility of fetuses and infants to methylmercury poisoning.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Data from Iraq have confirmed that methylmercury can pass to a child *in utero*, and mercury levels were equal to or higher in the newborn child than in the mother.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] In 1974, a joint Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) and World Health Organization (WHO) meeting made several recommendations to prevent a similar outbreak.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] These included stressing the importance of labelling bags in the local language and with locally understood warning symbols.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The possibility of an additive creating a strong bitter taste was studied.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The meeting urged governments to strictly regulate methyl- and ethylmercury use in their respective countries, including limiting use to where no other reasonable alternative was available.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] It also recommended the involvement of the FAO and WHO in assisting national governments in regulation and enforcement, and the setting up of national poison control centres.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Over 9–13 November, a Conference on Intoxication due to Alkylmercury-Treated Seed was held in Baghdad.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] It supported the recommendations of the FAO/WHO report and suggested that local and national media should publicise outbreaks, including size and symptoms; it considered the distribution of this information crucial.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] It also laid out a general plan as to the collection of relevant information from the field and potential analysis for further investigation.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] It called on national governments to make use of WHO involvement whenever feasible, and absolved world governments in clear terms, saying that "No country should ever feel that any blame will attach to it for allowing an outbreak to occur".
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-san-francisco-bay-oil-spill] The **1971 San Francisco Bay oil spill** occurred when two Standard Oil Company of California tankers, the *Arizona Standard* and the *Oregon Standard*, collided on January 18, 1971, in the San Francisco Bay.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-san-francisco-bay-oil-spill] Several environmental organizations had their origins in the spill cleanup.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-san-francisco-bay-oil-spill] Standard Oil spent more than $1 million on the clean-up.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-san-francisco-bay-oil-spill] In March 1971, California's Fish and Game Department estimated that 7,000 birds were oiled during the incident, most of which died before collection or while being taken care of.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-san-francisco-bay-oil-spill] At the end of January 1971, roughly 200 of the 1,600 birds "brought in" were still alive.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-san-francisco-bay-oil-spill] Ultimately less than 80 of those survived.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-san-francisco-bay-oil-spill] The resulting environmental destruction from the spill, specifically the avian population, prompted volunteers to rescue some 4,300 birds.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-san-francisco-bay-oil-spill] At the time, knowledge on how to care for oiled birds was low.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-san-francisco-bay-oil-spill] Despite best efforts, only 300 or so animals were deemed fit to be released.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-san-francisco-bay-oil-spill] The remnants of this volunteer force eventually resulted in the creation of the International Bird Rescue to increase knowledge and research in bird rescue.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/1971-san-francisco-bay-oil-spill] One of the largest volunteer turnouts since the 1906 San Francisco earthquake came of this event.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/2018-cargill-strike] The **2018 Cargill strike** was an American protest held by employees of the Dayton, Virginia United States plant of Cargill, a poultry manufacturing corporation.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/2018-cargill-strike] Plans of employees organizing and a union forming date back to late 2017 in the wake of reported employee abuse and poor working conditions at the plant.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/2018-cargill-strike] In November 2017, a solidarity community group, known as the Community Solidarity with Poultry Workers, formed in the wake of claimed employee abuse at Cargill.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/2018-cargill-strike] Specifically employees, and former employees claimed that the company would "dispose" of employees and not offer them proper health treatment.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/2018-cargill-strike] In February 2018, it was reported that local activists and Cargill union organizers had filed a charge against Cargill for retaliation against their employees for forming and organizing.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/2018-cargill-strike] In response to terminated employees, the community of Dayton organized a series of protests during the spring of 2018 to raise awareness of the strikes, and union organizing.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/2018-cargill-strike] The protests took place outside of the factory, but moved towards the parking lot as union leaders demanded to meet with plant leadership.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/2018-cargill-strike] In response the Dayton Police were dispatched and arrested nine protesters for trespassing on private property.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/2018-cargill-strike] The Dayton Police Department were dispatched and arrested nine individuals for protesting on private property.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/2018-cargill-strike] Cargill denied that the protestors and organized workers had scheduled a meeting with the plant's leadership, and denied that they fired three employees for forming a union.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/a-place-at-the-table] Participant Media is the entertainment company behind the film, and it is distributed by Magnolia Pictures.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/a-place-at-the-table] The Participant/Magnolia team is also responsible for the film *Food, Inc.* (2008).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/a-place-at-the-table] The film was originally titled *Finding North* but the name was later changed to *A Place at the Table*.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/a-place-at-the-table] As of 2012, about 50 million Americans were food insecure.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/a-place-at-the-table] This was approximately 1 in 6 of the overall population, with the proportion of children facing food insecurity even higher at about 1 in 4.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/a-place-at-the-table] One in every two children receive federal food assistance.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/a-place-at-the-table] Other Americans struggling with hunger are also featured, including a cop whose monthly paychecks only leaves him enough money to buy food for two weeks, forcing him to use a food bank.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/a-place-at-the-table] There is also a companion book titled *A Place at the Table: The Crisis of 49 Million Hungry Americans and How to Solve It,* edited by Peter Pringle and published by Public Affairs.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/a-place-at-the-table] The book features contributions from Jeff Bridges, Ken Cook, Marion Nestle, Bill Shore, Joel Berg, Robert Egger, Janet Poppendieck, David Beckmann, Mariana Chilton, Tom Colicchio, Jennifer Harris, Andy Fisher, Kelly Meyer and directors Kristi Jacobson and Lori Silverbush.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/a-place-at-the-table] The film was nominated for Grand Jury Prize at the 2012 Sundance Film Festival.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/a-place-at-the-table] At the 2013 IDA Documentary Awards, the film received the Pare Lorentz Award, which recognizes films for model filmmaking while focusing on the use of the natural environment, and justice for all and the illumination of pressing social problems.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/a-place-at-the-table] As of October 2015, it has a 90% approval ratings from 61 professional reviews aggregated by Rotten Tomatoes.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The city expanded quickly after the construction of a new wharf in 1931, followed by its designation as the capital city of the then-French colony in 1933.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The completion of the Vridi Canal in 1951 enabled Abidjan to become an important sea port.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Abidjan remained the capital of Ivory Coast after its independence from France in 1960.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] In 1983, the city of Yamoussoukro was designated as the official political capital of Ivory Coast.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] However, Abidjan has officially been designated as the "economic capital" of the country, because it is the largest city in the country and the centre of its economic activity.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Many political institutions and all foreign embassies continue to be located in Abidjan as well.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The Abidjan Autonomous District, which encompasses the city and some of its suburbs, is one of the 14 districts of Ivory Coast.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] According to oral tradition of the Tchaman as reported in the *Encyclopedic Dictionary of Côte d'Ivoire*, the name "Abidjan" results from a misunderstanding.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Legend states that an old man carrying branches to repair the roof of his house met a European explorer who asked him the name of the nearest village.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The old man did not speak the language of the explorer, and thought that he was being asked to justify his presence in that place.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Terrified by this unexpected meeting, he fled shouting "*min-chan m'bidjan*", which means in the Ebrié language: "I just cut the leaves." The explorer, thinking that his question had been answered, recorded the name of the locale as *Abidjan*.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] A slightly different and less elaborate version of the legend: When the first colonists asked a native man the name of the place, the man misunderstood and replied "*M'bi min djan*": "I've just been cutting leaves".
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Abidjan was originally a small Atchan fishing village.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] In 1896, following a series of deadly yellow fever epidemics, French colonists who had initially settled in Grand-Bassam decided to move to a safer place and in 1898 chose the current location of Abidjan.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The settlers were followed by the colonial government, created in 1899.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] But then nearby Bingerville became the capital of the French colony, from 1900 until 1934.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The future Abidjan, situated on the edge of the *lagoon n'doupé* ("the lagoon in hot water"), offered more land and greater opportunities for trade expansion.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The wharf in Petit Bassam (now Port-Bouët) south of town quickly overtook the wharf of Grand-Bassam in importance, and became the main point of economic access to the colony.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] In 1904, the rail terminus was located in the Port-Bouët area of Abidjan.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Starting in 1904, when Bingerville was not yet complete, Abidjan became the main economic hub of the colony of Ivory Coast and a prime channel for distributing products to the European hinterland, particularly through the Lebanese community, which was increasing in importance.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Henri de Fougères became governor of French Sudan in 1924, and remained governor until his death in 1931.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] One of the main streets of Abidjan still bears his name.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] In 1931, Plateau and what would become Treichville were connected by a floating bridge, more or less where the Houphouët-Boigny Bridge stands today.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The year 1931 also saw addresses begin to be assigned to the streets of Abidjan for the first time.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The addressing project was temporarily concluded in 1964, under the leadership of Mayor Konan Kanga, then badly redone American-style in 1993.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Abidjan became the third capital of Ivory Coast by a 1934 decree, following Grand-Bassam and Bingerville.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The decision to designate Abidjan as the capital spurred from its railroad that would connect the North and South regions of the Ivorian colony.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Several villages in Tchaman were then deserted.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The leader of the Tchaman community can still be found in Adjame ("center" or "meeting" in Tchaman), north of the Plateau.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] South of the Plateau district (the current central district of the city of Abidjan), the village of *Dugbeo* was moved across the lagoon to Anoumabo, "the forest of fruit bats", which became the neighborhood of Treichville (now known as Commikro, city of clerks).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Treichville was renamed in 1934, in honour of Marcel Treich-Laplène (1860–1890), the first explorer of the Ivory Coast and its first colonial administrator, considered its founder.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Instead of Dugbeyo, is the current Treich-Laplénie Avenue, the bus station and water lagoon buses in Plateau, and the Avenue Charles de Gaulle (commonly called Rue du Commerce).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The city was laid out like most colonial towns, on a grid plan.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Le Plateau ("m'brato" in Tchaman) were inhabited by settlers.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] In the north, the city was inhabited by the colonized.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The two zones were separated by the Gallieni Military Barracks, where now there is the current courthouse.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] City spaces were often segregated between French colonists and Ivorian natives.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Near the port, originally named Boulevard de Marseille, settlers became defensive and stole a street sign of a famous street of Marseille renamed the street Canebière, a sand track.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] This is the legend behind the first Blohorn oil mills, in Cocody and a racetrack was built in the south of the city.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] In Le Plateau in the 1940s, the Bardon Park Hotel was built, the first air-conditioned hotel working in francophone Africa.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Under the *Pacte Colonial* (Colonial Pact), Abidjan served as a port city that would connect the colonial hinterlands that produced raw materials to the industrial centers of France.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The construction of the 15m-deep Vridi Canal in 1950 aided in this endeavor by connecting the Ebrié Lagoon to the sea.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] By the late 1950s, Abidjan became the financial center of West Africa, challenging the dominance of Dakar.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] In 1958, the first bridge to connect Petit-Bassam Island with the mainland was completed.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] During World War II, France's Vichy government completed construction of the Port in Abidjan to counter British influence.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] After the war, France competed with other harbors in the Gulf of Guinea, and due to increased foreign interest in the capital city, placed protectionist policies on imports, foreign consulates, and U.S. building contracts.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The Abidjan city council elections of 1945 sparked the beginnings of the nationalist movement that challenged France's authority.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] When Ivory Coast became independent in 1960, Abidjan became the new country's administrative and economic center.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The axis south of Treichville, towards the international airport and the beaches, became the heart of European and middle-class Abidjan.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The city saw considerable population growth in the decades following independence, expanding from 180,000 inhabitants in 1960 to 1,269,000 in 1978.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Abidjan's skyline dates back to the economic prosperity of this period.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] New districts such as the upmarket Cocody were founded during this period; built to a large extent in a colonial style, Cocody has since become home to Ivory Coast's wealthy classes as well as expatriates and foreign diplomats.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The district is home to the embassy of France, Hotel Ivoire (which for a long time, was the only African hotel to have a skating rink), and, since 2009, the largest U.S. embassy in West Africa.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Paul's Cathedral, designed by Italian architect Aldo Spirito, began with the 1980 groundbreaking by Pope John Paul II and was completed in 1985.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] From the 1980s, Abidjan's fortunes declined as a result of negligence on the part of officials as well as corruption and general degradation.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] In 1983, the village of Yamoussoukro became the new political capital of Ivory Coast under the leadership of President Félix Houphouët-Boigny, who was born in Yamoussoukro.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] From 2002 to 2007 and especially from 2010 to 2011, Abidjan suffered from the consequences of the First and Second Ivorian Civil Wars.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] In November 2004, armed conflict broke out between French forces and Ivorian forces loyal to Laurent Gbagbo after the Ivorian Air Force attacked French peacekeepers in northern Ivory Coast.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] After France destroyed Ivory Coast's air capabilities in retaliation, pro-Gbagbo groups staged riots and looting in Abidjan and targeted French homes, schools, and businesses.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] French peacekeepers moved into the city to calm the situation.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Other crises during the first civil war period include the case of the *Probo Koala* in 2006, in which disposed products caused thousands of residents to seek medical attention.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Ivory Coast's civil conflicts seriously impacted the security situation in Abidjan.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Amidst the anti-French riots in November 2004, 4,000 prisoners in Abidjan escaped from the country's largest prison.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Abidjan was one of the main theaters of the 2010–2011 Ivorian crisis and the site of major demonstrations against incumbent president Gbagbo, including one on International Women's Day in 2011 that saw several demonstrators killed by Gbagbo's forces.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Civil postwar violence persisted in urban districts with high territorial control by Ggabo's supporters.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Districts became associated with specific political attributes, which Ggabo's forces used to target residents in Abobo and Yopougon.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Ethnic homogeneity in segregated neighborhoods is suggested to have enabled such territorial turmoil.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The end of the crisis came with Gbagbo's capture in Abidjan in April 2011, following a major offensive by forces loyal to election winner Alassane Ouattara with support from France and the UN.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Overtime, the intensity of postwar violence has decreased.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] In 2025, a major overhaul of names from the colonial era will be reorganized to more African names.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Abidjan lies on the south-east coast of the country, on the Gulf of Guinea.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The city is located on the Ébrié Lagoon.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The business district, Le Plateau, is the center of the city, along with Cocody, Deux Plateaux (the city's wealthiest neighborhood and a hub for diplomats), and Adjamé, a slum on the north shore of the lagoon.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Treichville and Marcory lie to the south, Attecoube, Locodjro, Abobo Doume and Yopougon to the west, and Île Boulay is located in the middle of the lagoon.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Further south lies Port Bouët, home to the airport and main seaport.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Abidjan experiences a tropical wet and dry climate, according to the Köppen climate classification (Köppen climate classification: **Aw**), closely bordering a tropical monsoon climate.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Abidjan has nonconsecutive rainy seasons (precipitation above 60 millimetres (2.4 in) with a long rainy season from March to July and a short rainy season from September to December, and three dry months (January, February and August).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Precipitation is abundant during the summer months, except for August, due to activation of the Benguela Current, which reduces the precipitation total throughout the month.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The Benguela Current also lowers the mean temperature during August, making it the coolest month of the year, averaging 24.5 °C (76.1 °F).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Abidjan has two additional dry months (January and February).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Abidjan is generally humid, with average relative humidity above 80% throughout the year.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The annual temperature would increase by 1.8 °C (3.2 °F), and the temperature of the coldest month by 1.9 °C (3.4 °F), but the temperature of the warmest month would be 3.4 °C (6.1 °F) higher.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] According to Climate Action Tracker, the current warming trajectory appears consistent with 2.7 °C (4.9 °F), which closely matches RCP 4.5.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Moreover, according to the 2022 IPCC Sixth Assessment Report, Abidjan is one of 12 major African cities (Abidjan, Alexandria, Algiers, Cape Town, Casablanca, Dakar, Dar es Salaam, Durban, Lagos, Lomé, Luanda and Maputo) which would be the most severely affected by the future sea level rise.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] It estimates that they would collectively sustain cumulative damages of US$65 billion under RCP 4.5 and US$86.5 billion for the high-emission scenario RCP 8.5 by the year 2050.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Since sea level rise would continue for about 10,000 years under every scenario of climate change, future costs of sea level rise would only increase, especially without adaptation measures.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The 10 communes of the former City of Abidjan are traditionally divided into northern Abidjan and southern Abidjan, with the Ébrié Lagoon separating both halves of the city.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Towns near Abidjan include Jacqueville, Grand-Lahou and Dabou in the west; Sikensi, Tiassalé, Agboville, Adzopé and Alépé in the north; and Grand-Bassam to the east.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The towns (or sub-prefectures) of Anyama, Bingerville, Brofodoumé and Songon are within the Abidjan Department, which is co-extensive with the autonomous district.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Formerly managed by the French colonial administration, Abidjan became a municipality (commune) in 1956, divided into administrative areas by lagoons.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Its first municipal council was elected on 18 November 1956, and the first mayor in the context of the Loi-Cadre of 1956 was president Félix Houphouët-Boigny.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] In 1980, the municipality of Abidjan (*commune d'Abidjan*) was transformed into the City of Abidjan (*Ville d'Abidjan*), and its territory was divided in 10 communes.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] A city council and mayor of the City of Abidjan elected by the population oversaw the entire city, whereas 10 municipal councils also elected by the population managed each commune.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Dioulo Emmanuel was elected mayor of the City of Abidjan on 30 November 1980.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] In 2001, the City of Abidjan was disbanded and replaced by a larger Autonomous District of Abidjan.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The autonomous district overlaps the Abidjan Department, which was established in 1969 and has had its current boundaries since 1998.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The district is made up of the 10 communes of the former City of Abidjan, and of 4 outlying sub-prefectures: Anyama, Bingerville, Brofodoumé, and Songon.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Since the 2000s, the built-up area of Abidjan has largely expanded into these 4 formerly rural sub-prefectures.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] As a result of the creation of the Autonomous District of Abidjan in 2001, the post of Mayor of City of Abidjan was replaced by that of District Governor, appointed by the head of state.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The position has been occupied by Ibrahim Bacongo Cissé since 2023.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Each of the ten communes of Abidjan has its own municipal council, headed by a mayor.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The last municipal elections were held in 2018.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The sub-prefectures of the autonomous district also have their own mayors and councils.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The communes of Abobo, Adjamé, Attécoubé, Cocody, and Plateau are located north of the Ébrié Lagoon (hence the name "Abidjan North").
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] This is the continental part of Abidjan.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The commune of Yopougon straddles the lagoon, with part lying north and part south of that body of water.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The communes of Treichville, Koumassi, Marcory, and Port-Bouet in Abidjan are south of the lagoon.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Blokosso and Locodjro villages are included within the city and maintain cultural identity in urban areas.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The Université Félix Houphouët-Boigny was founded in 1964.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] In Ivory Coast, the enrollment rate is 74% and access to secondary education is limited by an entrance assessment at the 6th stage after which one-third of students are allowed to continue their studies.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] 24% of the student population resides in Abidjan, which comprises 20% of the total population.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Abidjan is the location of the main educational institutions in Ivory Coast.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] These include the Lycée Classique d'Abidjan, the Lycée Sainte-Marie de Cocody, Lycée garçon de Bingerville, and Mami Adjoua the Lyceum.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The Blaise Pascal Abidjan school is a French school – a school who has signed an agreement with the AEFE.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Recently the Lycée International Jean-Mermoz re-opened which was initially called College International Jean-Mermoz, founded by Pierre Padovani.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The Institution suffered from a devastating war and was forced to close.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The city also hosts a campus of the HEC Paris business school.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The majority of Ivorian government institutions are still located in Abidjan and have not been transferred to the political capital, Yamoussoukro.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The President's office is in Cocody, and the parliament, the Constitutional Council, the Supreme Court, and the Chancellery of the National Order are all in Le Plateau.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Under the presidency of Laurent Gbagbo (2000–11), efforts were made to give effect to the project of making the political capital Yamoussoukro in Côte d'Ivoire.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] This goal continues to be the consensus of the country's political leaders.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Government offices are located in Le Plateau in the administrative district of Abidjan, Boulevard Carde or Angoulvant Boulevard (near the Cathedral of St.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Paul of Abidjan), or elsewhere in the great buildings of the town.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The instability of the 2002–2007 civil war and 2010–2011 crisis saw foreign peacekeeping forces stationed in Abidjan.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The United Nations Operation in Côte d'Ivoire (UNOCI), established in April 2004, has its headquarters at the former Hotel Sebroko in Attécoubé.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] While the size of the force has been reduced since the end of the 2011 crisis, UNOCI's mandate was extended in 2013 and again in 2015.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The force remains authorized to maintain up to 5,245 troops, 192 observers, 1,500 police and eight customs officers in the country.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] France's peacekeeping operations in Ivory Coast continued under the aegis of Operation Unicorn until 2015 and then as the French forces in Côte d'Ivoire from 2015 onward.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] In 2014, French defense minister Jean-Yves Le Drian announced that Abidjan would be reinforced as the entry point for France's military presence and counterterrorism operations in the Sahel region.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] After al-Qaeda militants targeted beachgoers at Grand-Bassam in March 2016, the French government announced it would increase its troop deployment in Côte d'Ivoire from 500 to 900.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] French soldiers are based in Port-Bouet as well as at the Abidjan airport.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] In 2007, Pierre Laba's comedy film *Permanent Danger* explored the laxity of the police against banditry in major African cities, specifically in Abidjan.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Abidjan is divided into districts, each of which has a police station.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The municipal police and national police are separate.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] All police are trained at the National Police Academy in the town of Cocody.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] They are recruited by competitive examination held by the police administration.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The Force and CECOS accompany the police.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The main base of the gendarmerie is at Agban (commonly Adjamé).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] A training school is in Cocody and the city.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Since 2000, Ivory Coast has experienced a sharp rise in drug trafficking.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Drug dens arise mainly in informal settlements and there has been a recent spike in demand among unemployed youth and Ivorian vagrants.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The Ivorian police increasingly focus on the fight against trafficking and drug use in the district of Abidjan.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] A report by the Office of the UN says West Africa plays an increasingly important role in the transit of cocaine between Latin America and Europe.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] In May 2007, seven drug houses were dismantled and 191 people arrested including a military officer.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Abidjan is home to Port-Bouet, one of the six French military bases that still exist in Africa (Dakar, Libreville, Bouar CAR, N'Djamena and Djibouti).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Thousands of people live there, around the 43rd BIMA which is permanently in place in accordance with established defence agreements on 24 April 1961 linking the two countries.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Diplomatic missions in Ivory Coast are mostly located in Abidjan.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The African Development Bank (ADB), the largest financial institution in Africa, is headquartered in Abidjan.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The 2021 census recorded Abidjan's population as 6,321,017.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] As Abidjan is inhabited by people from a wide array of different ethnicities, French is commonly spoken in the metropolitan area, which is the third largest French speaking metropolitan area in the world after Kinshasa and Paris.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Colloquial Abidjan French has even appeared, which has a different pronunciation and some slang words different from standard French.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Abidjan is recognized as one of the few areas in Africa where French (colloquial Abidjan French) is truly a native tongue, along with Libreville, Gabon.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The District of Abidjan's population was 6,321,017 at the 14 December 2021 census, up from 4,707,404 at the 15 May 2014 census.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Population increase, lower in the 2000s due to the economic crisis and Ivorian Civil War, has picked up in the 2010s to levels unseen since the 1980s thanks to the rapid economic growth experienced by Abidjan after the return of peace in 2012.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Many inhabitants come to live in Abidjan for employment and better standards of living.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] By 1950, Abidjan had just exceeded a population of 50,000 (at the end of 1948).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Reaching a population of a million by the end of 1975, the city grew at a rate of 10 to 12% per year, doubling every six or seven years.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] However, this growth underwent a sharp decline due to the crises of the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] In the last 20 years of the 20th century, the growth rate dropped to 3–6%.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Birth rate growth was supplemented by migration, with the influx being substantial and the outflow only partly offseting the arrivals.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The migration, prior to the census of 1988, contributed a growth of about 80,000 with 50,000 people from within Ivory Coast, and about 30,000 from abroad per year.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] From within Ivory Coast, the migration pattern was dominated by Akan (South-east, 48%), then Mandé (North-west, 24%) and Krou (South-west, 20%).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] From abroad, the migration was Burkinabes (30%), Malians (22%), Ghanaians (19%), Nigerien (11%), and Guineans (9%).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Of the non-African migration, Lebanese migration was highest, followed by European migration, with the French being largest of this latter group.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] All in all, people of non-African origin represent 3% of the total population of Abidjan, which remains the highest in the region.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The traditional language of the city's region is Ebrié.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Since the colonial period, the official language in Abidjan and throughout Côte d'Ivoire has been French.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Another form of spoken French in Abidjan is *Nouchi*, a highly informal variety used as adolescent slang.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The historical lingua franca, still spoken and understood by most of the trading population of Abidjan, is Dioula.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The city is home to Ivorians from throughout the country and about sixty vernacular languages are spoken, such as Attié, Baoulé, Bété, and Wobé.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Abidjan is surrounded by more than thirty villages where Baoulé and Ébrié are still commonly spoken.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Some traditional medicine establishments sell traditional drugs in the street.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] There are numerous health centers, pharmacies and pharmacopoeias.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The city has more than fifty clinics, and over sixty specialist locations (veterinary, dermatology, dental, optometry, motherhood, psychology, pediatrics, etc.).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Modern districts like Plateau or Cocody have developed similar to those in Europe with the construction of large office towers and apartment buildings between the 1970s and the mid-1980s.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The CCIA building (Abidjan International Trade Center Building), a skyscraper, was completed in 1982.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Traditional neighborhoods like Treichville or Marcory maintained the system of "concessions" where housing is adjacent to the plant and an area of several houses, within the normal organization and multi centuries-old African villages.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The district of Cocody is also home to many single-storey wooden villas, surrounded by vast gardens of lush vegetation, fed by the heavy rains that water the city.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Wealthier inhabitants constructed villas in imitation of Greek temples in this district.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] In addition, many houses were built on stilts on the edge of the Ébrié Lagoon.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The town hall, a fine example of modernist architecture, was designed by architect Henri Chomette.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The urban network is disrupted, as Abidjan has seen its population double every seven years since 1945.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Rural people are attracted by the opportunities of the city.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Abidjan represents 45% of city dwellers in Ivory Coast and 20% of the overall population.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The city is by far the country's largest, dwarfing the second-largest city, Bouaké (which had 542,082 inhabitants in 2014) as well as the political capital, Yamoussoukro (207,412 inhabitants).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Since the 2006 Probo Koala toxic waste dumping incident, significant efforts have been made to address waste management issues in Abidjan.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] In 2006, a contract was signed between China and Ivory Coast: a Chinese company handling urban waste and industrial plans to treat all waste district this transformation also create daily cleaning.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] French nongovernmental organisation ACTED rolled out a three-part project across three districts of Abidjan in 2016, establishing street cleaning, waste collection and hygiene training.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] ACTED spokesperson Jérémy Lescot described the project as "a fine success".
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The last transportation upgrade in Abidjan led to the repaving of certain roads in the capital in 1994.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Since May 2007, the company Ageroute (Road Management Agency) is undertaking major operations in Abidjan and Anyama relating to badly damaged roads, suffering from lack of maintenance, heavy rain and protests.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] It is also addressing the gutters and unpaved roads.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The District and BNETD plan to rehabilitate and construct 400 to 500 miles (640–800 kilometres), providing them with a quality to last 15–20 years of life.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Improvements include the rehabilitation of roads in Abidjan and Anyama, construction of drains, the tarring of gravel roads and sanitation of the city by the construction of sewers.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] The principal stock exchange of Ivory Coast and the other seven countries of the Union Économique et Monétaire Ouest Africaine (UEMOA), Bourse Régionale des Valeurs Mobilières (BRVM), is located in Abidjan.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Air Ivoire had its head office in Abidjan.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p01] Prior to its dissolution, Air Afrique was headquartered in Abidjan.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The region near the lagoons is the most industrialized region of the country.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Major industries include food processing, lumber, automobile manufacturing, textiles, chemicals, and soap.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Its industries are mainly in construction and maintenance with the presence of major international groups: the furnace SETAO, Colas, Bouygues, Jean Lefebvre, and Swiss Holcim.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] There are textile industries with the packaging of cotton in the north both for export or for on-site processing of cloth, canvas, batik clothing and miscellaneous.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The textile sector is very dynamic, and represents 15.6% of net investment, 13% of turnover and 24% of the value added in Ivorian industry.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] There are several offshore oil wells in operation (Côte d'Ivoire is an oil producing country), which leads to the presence of a chemical industry with oil refineries, and an oil port.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The city also has a large wood processing plant at the port by river from the forests of central Canada.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] It exports natural mahogany, peeled wood, plywood and chipboard for the past two centuries.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Food industry mainly include: the production of palm oil, bergamot and Seville oranges.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] In the west, rubber is processed as well as manufacturing beverages from pineapples, oranges and mangoes, producing robusta coffee: Côte d'Ivoire is the third largest producer, behind Colombia and Brazil and processing cocoa, it is the largest producer in the world ahead of Ghana and Indonesia.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] (37% of cocoa and 10% of coffee products undergo at least one first local processing).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Abidjan is also the first African tuna port for the European market.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] This generated 3,000 salaried jobs and is an important source of foreign exchange.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] As in all countries of the Third World developing countries, much of the city's economy lies in what economists describe as informal economy with its many "odd jobs".
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The development of tertiary industry, with the establishment of international commercial banks and the increasing number of service companies of all types, appears to be the trend of recent years.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Abidjan is the main financial center of French West Africa.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The seat of the common stock exchange of West Africa (BRVM) is located in Abidjan.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] BRVM is mainly dominated by Ivorian firms.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The thermal power plant Azito, built in 1997 in partnership with EDF, located on the Yopougon on the edge of the lagoon and facing Ébrié Island Boulay, alone provides 300 MW.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Two other power plants, built in 1984 and 1985, are installed in Vridi.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The production, which increases steadily, and gas storage are provided by two state companies: PETROCI and GESTOCI.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] A small industry of renewable energy production has also developed.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The city has a powerful fixed telephone network of 450,000 lines (in 2004) managed by *Côte d'Ivoire Telecom*.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Broadband Internet connections, leased lines and ADSL are powered by various providers: Aviso Ivory Coast Telecoms.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Abidjan is home to all the representatives of international financial institutions: World Bank, International Monetary Fund, African Development Bank, BOAD, etc.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Banking Commission of WAEMU regional stock exchange securities subsidiaries of major international banks: BNP Paribas, General bank, Crédit Lyonnais, Citibank, JPMorgan Chase & Co., Barclays, etc.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Sixteen national banks (SGBCI, BICI, etc.) maintaining a network of 170 branches, seven financial institutions and more than thirty insurance companies make a financial competitive Abidjan that animates the entire West Africa.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Trains on the line to Ouagadougou run from several stations in the city, the most important being in Treichville.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Ferries link Treichville, Abobo-Doumé and Le Plateau.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Félix-Houphouët-Boigny International Airport serves the city.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Work on a new metro system has begun, with the beginning of service expected in 2028.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] SOTRA (Abidjan Transport Company) ensure urban transportation in Abidjan via bus, taxi and luggage Line Express.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] SOTRA has announced the start of work for the use of light rail to Abidjan.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The project has three phases at a cost of 125 billion CFA francs for a long loop of 32 km.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] There are two kinds: the taxi-meter (red), which can travel throughout the city, and woro-woro (yellow and green, blue or orange depending on the commune), which are limited to a neighborhood.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Port Bouet Airport has a large capacity that allows it to accommodate all existing large aircraft.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Abidjan is located an hour's flight from all the capitals of the sub-region.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Abidjan is served by major airlines in the direction of the great capitals of the world.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Headquarters of the former multinational African Air company, Abidjan airport had nearly 2,070,000 passengers in 2017.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The District has several paved streets and boulevards linking the towns between them and the District across the country.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Abidjan has a network of urban bypasses.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] River transport is already consistent with fishing spots and many "boat-buses" connecting the various neighborhoods of the city thrives plan lagoon.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Abidjan is also the bridgehead of the country's only highway linking the city to the administrative and political capital, Yamoussoukro.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Abidjan has one of the biggest ports in the sub-region (West Africa).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] It is a container transshipment port and was opened in 1951 in the presence of the Minister of Overseas and Colonies at the time, François Mitterrand.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The 15 m deep Vridi Canal, where boats with large draughts can dock in the deep-water port.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Ivory Coast is in the Franc Zone (where the currency is CFA francs), as part of the West African Economic and Monetary Union (WAEMU).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Abidjan is the economic centre of both the Côte d'Ivoire and of the whole region, including Burkina Faso and Mali; this is mainly because of its deep-water port.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The road network in Abidjan (5,600 km asphalted in 1995, compared to 1,000 km in 1970), which covers the whole region, effectively increases its port activity as 50% of the business from Burkina Faso, Mali and Niger pass through it.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Abidjan receives the bulk of the country's industrial activity; its port alone receiving 60% of ivory park industry.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Abidjan has ambitions of oil-production—off-shore production and especially refining and distribution.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] In 1995 the port received 12 million tonnes of traffic, of which 5.5 million tonnes were petroleum products.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Exports include coffee, cocoa, timber, bananas, pineapples, and manganese.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Alassane Ouattara Bridge, completed in 2023, is the 5th bridge over the Abidjan lagoon.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The two-halves of the city, Northern Abidjan and Southern Abidjan, are joined by the Houphouët-Boigny, the Charles de Gaulle and the Henri Konan Bédié bridges.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The two former bridges, built in the 1950s and 1960s respectively, are located between Treichville and Le Plateau.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The Général-de-Gaulle Bridge extends over the immense Valéry Giscard d'Estaing Boulevard which leads to the airport.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Both bridges are often congested, especially during rush hour or on the occasion of police and military roadblocks.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] A third 1.5 km (0.93 mi) toll bridge and expressway, the Henri Konan Bédié Bridge between Cocody and Marcory was completed in December 2014.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Project construction began in the second half of 2012 and required the relocation of several homes and businesses opposite the Mille Maquis (the noted restaurant *la Bâche bleue* was moved).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] According to data reported by the African Development Bank, 2,499 persons were impacted by the bridge construction and were relocated and compensated.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] A fourth 1.4 km (0.87 mi) 8-lane toll bridge between Yopougon and Plateau was built between 2018 and 2024.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] A fifth 630 m (690 yd) 4-lane toll-free bridge, the Alassane Ouattara Bridge between Cocody and Plateau, was built between 2019 and 2023.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The city is the foothold for the region's only railway: the Abidjan-Ouagadougou line, with stations in Treichville, Abobo and Adjamé.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] This line only has two trains, the *Gazelle* and the *Bélier*, and links the two capitals in about 40 hours.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The most recent project in Abidjan is the Abidjan Metro which is promised by the Ivory Society of Railroads (SICF).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The development of infrastructural projects has been envisaged, including a suburban train system in Abidjan which is estimated to cost almost 100 billion CFA francs.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] This suburban train system would link the North-West to the East and North of the city.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The project extends over 25 km of railway tracks which as of 2011 were used by the operator Sitarail, a subsidiary company of the Bolloré group.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The infrastructural works (tracks, electrification, and civil engineers) have been estimated at 40 billion CFA francs, financed by the State of Ivory Coast and backers (World Bank and the French Development Agency).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] In addition, a BOT concession contract would be given to a private operator, over 20–30 years, to operate the network.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] This operator will be in charge of the acquisition of railway materials, workshop renovation and the implementation of an organisational system.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The concession contract has been estimated to be around 60 billion CFA francs.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Its nicknames, such as "Manhattan of the tropics", "Small Manhattan" or "Pearl of the lagoons", explain the city's unpredictable and triumphant image.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] With its accommodation facilities – such as the Golf Hôtel – and sporting facilities, its lively night life, transport and communication lines as well as its impressiveness, it is the perfect city for business tourism.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Abidjan also has beaches around the lagoon, with palm and coconut trees, in the Vridi area, which are very popular at weekends with the picturesque sight of the pineapple and coconut sellers.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Nevertheless, the rip-tides which affects practically the whole of the Gulf of Guinea's coast, means that in this area swimming is not usually allowed.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Generally, in Cote d'Ivoire, tourism has never really been developed as an economic industry; the country is not much of a common holiday destination.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Converted in 1926, this park has 3,000 hectares and ancient "sacred wood" lies at the entrance to the city, in the Attécoubé community, which has been conserved as a relic of the first forest which surrounded the lagoon in the past.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] A tarmaced road goes straight to the lake at the heart of the park and trails go throughout it.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The park is inhabited and there are coffee and cocoa plantations.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] At the edge of the park, a small river serves as a wash-house where the *fanicos*, laundry men, work after collecting the laundry from the whole of the city.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] It is one of the 'small jobs' which exist in Abidjan.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The district has an abundance of night-clubs, maquis, out-door areas, and go-go bars.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] These entertainment platforms provide a musical 'pipeline' encompassing mainly DJs, Coupé Décalé and Zouglou, and, in lesser amounts, other local and international varieties.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Formerly containing only local traditional varieties, Congolese music and Western music, Abidjan's night life has experienced a positive cultural disruption in its music since the start of the 2000s, with the arrival of Coupé Décalé.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] This musical genre was introduced in 2002 by Douk Saga and La Jet Set, with the help of Sagacité, created a phenomenon which has not stopped spreading and reaching out to the hot nights in the capitals of the sub-region.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] It has given a globally identifiable cultural identity to entertainment 'made in Côte d'Ivoire'.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The very popular Zouglou additionally benefits "Wôyô" spaces; furnished and dedicated so that the most famous, the Internat at Fitini's and the Lycee at Vieux Gazeur's, attract 'zouglouphiles' the whole weekend.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Treichville, with its many maquis, discothèques, and jazz clubs, used to be the liveliest area in the city, but since the end of the 1990s Youpougon, Marcory, and Cocody have taken over this role.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Abidjan is a turntable for West African music, and a major producer of musical art in Africa.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The city attracts the majority of musicians from the Côte d'Ivoire mainly because of its many dance clubs, which allow artists to make their debut and express themselves, record companies and national media.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Here are a few examples of the most popular artists to have made their debut in Abidjan: Alpha Blondy, Aïcha Koné, the group Magic System, Meiway, and Tiken Jah Fakoly, as well as Gadji Celi, Chantal Taiba, Nayanka Bell, DJ Arafat.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] In the 1980s, South African musician Miriam Makeba relocated to Abidjan when she was not allowed back into the country, as did the Congolese singer Tshala Muana.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Since the 1990s, Abidjan has had a significant variety of musical styles being exported throughout Africa and the West.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] These are Zoblazo, Mapouka, Zouglou and, since 2002, the Coupé-Décalé; the popularity and great variety of these dances make the city a kind of African dance and musical trend capital.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The Democratic Republic of the Congo formerly held this title, with rumba, soukous and then ndombolo.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Abidjan is also considered the reggae capital of Africa.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Most mass media in Côte d'Ivoire can be found in Abidjan.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The National Council for Audio-visual Communication (CNCA) is the regulating authority of audio-visual material in Côte d'Ivoire.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Radiodiffusion Television Ivoirienne (RTI) is the radio and television broadcasting authority for Côte d'Ivoire; it is financed by licence fees, publicity and grants.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] RTI has four television channels and two radio stations: *La Première* (non-specialised), *TV2*, *RTI Music TV*, *RTI Sport TV*, *Radio Côte d'Ivoire*, and *Fréquence 2* (non-specialised radio).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] *Radio Jam* is a private radio station in Côte d'Ivoire and is most listened to by young people.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] With regards to private channels, Tam-Tam TV will be the first International Côte d'Ivoire television channel with headquarters in Abidjan, with other studios in the United States, Italy, France, Asia, the Middle East.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] There are also several Ivory Coast TV channels or radio stations available on the Internet: *Africahit*, *Music TV*, *Abidjan.net TV*, *Bengueshow*, etc.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] With the launch in 2015 of DISCOP Africa Abidjan, the city became a hub for TV market professionals from French-speaking Africa.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The advent of multiple parties in Côte d'Ivoiret in 1999 can be seen in the proliferation of newspapers and diverse publications, of which the majority is published in Abidjan.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The President, the Prime Minister, the government, and ministers have an official website.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Several fashion events are organised in the city each year: "Les Féeries" (The Fairies), the ceremonies for Miss Côte d'Ivoire, Miss Abidjan District, Miss Christmas (for 6- to 11-year-olds) and Miss Awoulaba (very prestigious).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Moreover, the Yéhé Fashion Show takes place every year, a celebration of African fashion, and the International Festival of Lingerie and Beauty of Abidjan (FILBA).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Abidjan is also the headquarters for Ivory Coast's clothes designers, renowned for being the best in Africa; including Gilles Touré (designer for Miss Côte d'Ivoire) or even Pathéo.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints has over 100 congregations in the area with a temple that was completed in May 2025.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Côte d'Ivoire is home to teams from several sports: (basketball, athletics, rugby, handball, volleyball, etc.), soccer is very popular in Abidjan.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Abidjan is home to ASEC Mimosas, one of the country's leading football clubs.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] In 1964, the *Jeux d'Abidjan* took place in Abidjan, as did the final of the African Cup Winners' Cup in 1975, 1980, 1983, and 1990, then another in 1992 under the name of CAF Confederations Cup.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The Stade Félix Houphouët-Boigny was the host of the very first African Super Cup in 1992, and the second in 1998.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The finals of the 1966, 1986, 1995, and 1998 CAF Champions League also took place in Abidjan.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The main football event organised in Abidjan was the 1984 African Cup of Nations and one of the finals of the 1983 African Youth Cup of Nations.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] The economic capital also attracted other football events such as the Assumption Tournament (the first one taking place in 2007 in the Stade Robert Champroux), the West African Club Championship (UFOA Cup), and international gala matches.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Abidjan is the centre of Ivorian rugby, and most of the Côte d'Ivoiret national rugby union team come from here.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/abidjan-p02] Although the origins of Ivorian rugby go back to the 1960s and earlier, French official Jean-François Turon managed the team at Abidjan University in the 1980s, but it was François Dali who created Ivorian rugby, and his son was the national captain during the 1990s.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The Ohlone people were the original inhabitants of Adobe Creek.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] A large shell mound which once had a group of Indian huts was found near Adobe Creek in Palo Alto.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Evidence of a smaller settlement within Los Altos was uncovered in 1971, when an Ohlone burial ground with skeletons—one with ceremonial beads—was uncovered by new construction along Adobe Creek near O'Keefe Lane.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The site had other artifacts, and an archeological dig was mounted by Foothill College in 1970.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Around this same time, an Ohlone basket was discovered buried in the Creek bank further north.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The O'Keefe site has a historical plaque at the entrance to Normandy Lane marking the historic site labeled "Ohlone Indian Village, Town of Los Altos Hills, Historical Site No.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] 1, Ohlone 10-L0-N11 Village Site Dedicated this day to the Ohlone People Whose ancestors made their homes here April 4, 1973.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Presented by American Association of University Women of Los Altos".
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] This Ohlone village site had an ideal location situated on the perennial reach of Adobe Creek between Interstate 280 and Foothill Expressway.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] On the 1862 Allardt Map the upper creek is called **Arroyo San Antonio** (**San Antonio Creek**) and the lower creek is called **Arroyo de las Yeguas** (**Yeguas Creek**).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] *Yeguas* is Spanish for "mare", and the Mission Santa Clara named it that because they built a corral for mares along the creek's banks near the Bay.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Juan Prado Mesa renamed it **San Antonio Creek** when he was granted Rancho San Antonio in 1839 by Governor Juan Bautista Alvarado.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The **Adobe Creek** name appears as early as 1855 on an official surveyor's map, which lists both the Adobe and San Antonio names for the creek.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] During the secularization of the missions in the 1830s, Alvarado parceled out much of their land to prominent Californios via land grants.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Mesa was a soldier stationed at the Presidio of San Francisco who had become alfarez (officer in command) in 1837.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] He built a large square adobe, which lasted well into the twentieth century as a crumbling ruin long thought of as a fortification.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The site today is on a hill on the southeast side of El Monte Avenue near Summerhill Avenue in Los Altos, California, most of which is located on the territory of the Rancho.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The upper creek originates in the historic Rancho La Purisima Concepcion, which was granted by Governor Alvarado in 1840 to Jose Gorgonio, an Indian living at Mission Santa Clara.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Gorgonio moved to the west bank of Adobe Creek near Fremont Avenue in Los Altos Hills.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Much of the town of Los Altos Hills, California was located on this Rancho.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] In 1844 Rancho La Purisima Concepcion was sold to Juana Briones de Miranda, whose family members had accompanied both the Gaspar de Portolà and the Juan Bautista de Anza Expeditions.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Designated a California State Historical Landmark in 1954, the 160-year-old Juana Briones home was scheduled for demolition in 2007 because of damage to it by the Loma Prieta earthquake in 1989.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] In 2009, it still stands and has been recently documented with a Historic American Buildings Survey (HABS).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] After 1831, Mexican rancho owners would logically erect their dwellings on or very near creeks.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Locally, Juan Prado's adobe was near Adobe Creek & Juanita Briones' adobe was near Barron Creek.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Because they were permanent features of the landscape, creeks were often used as Rancho boundaries.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] This was true locally, where the Mexican diseño show Adobe Creek as the boundary between Rancho San Antonio and Rancho La Purisima Concepcion.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] When Americans took over in 1850, speculators bought much of this land.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Much of it initially became large self-contained ranches—typically running cattle & growing crops like wheat, barley & oats that required little or no irrigation.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] That changed in a few decades when it was discovered that orchards and vineyards could thrive here.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Such agriculture of course used more water.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Local land was cut progressively into smaller holdings, until most of it was subdivided as the population increased.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] This meant more and more wells, including large ones dug along Adobe Creek by early water companies to serve the little town of Los Altos.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The water table inevitably shrank as a result, and alarms about this development appeared, at least as early as the 1920s.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] In the early 1930s, the Los Altos News reported that the water table, which stood at 120 feet in 1898, was now down to 335 feet.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The Trust for Hidden Villa is a nonprofit educational organization founded by Frank and Josephine Duveneck, who purchased most of the land comprising the upper Adobe Creek watershed in 1924.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] They opened Hidden Villa as a gathering place for discussion, reflection, and incubation of social reform.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Over the following decades, the Duvenecks also established the first Hostel on the Pacific Coast (1937), the first multiracial summer camp (1945), and Hidden Villa's Environmental Education Program (1970), all on the creek's upper reaches.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] John Warnock and Charles Geschke, the co-founders of the Adobe Systems software company, both lived next to Adobe Creek in Los Altos, and named their company after the creek.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The founder of Los Altos, Paul Shoup, picked a premium lot on Adobe Creek for his home from the ranch lands he helped purchase from Sarah Winchester that later became the community of Los Altos.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The Paul Shoup House on Adobe Creek is the first property in Los Altos to be listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Adobe Creek drains about 11 square miles (28 km2), arising at 2,600 feet (790 m) on the northeastern flank of Black Mountain in Los Altos Hills, California.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Adobe Creek was once a perennial stream, as evidenced by historical presence of steelhead trout (*Oncorhynchus mykiss*).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Trout young spend their first year in fresh water and obviously cannot survive in streams that run dry seasonally.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Historically, lawsuits were filed to prevent diversion of creek water for irrigation because they caused the creek to run "dry certain seasons of the year".
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Local lumberman, Herbert Bickell, reported catching steelhead year-round in Adobe Creek until the mid-1950s when the creek's flows became intermittent behind his home on Van Buren Street.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Today the creek's perennial sections are above Hidden Villa and between Foothill Expressway and Interstate 280 above the Manresa Way bridge.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Adobe Creek's upper tributaries are, in order, the **Middle Fork Adobe Creek**, then immediately the **West Fork Adobe Creek** (the West Fork is known locally as **Letcher Creek**).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Next the **North Fork Adobe Creek** (originating on Page Mill Road near "Shotgun Bend" at an elevation over 1500 feet) joins Adobe Creek by the Duveneck's main house at Hidden Villa.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The North Fork Adobe Creek is also known locally as **Bunny Creek**.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The upper watershed of Adobe Creek is completely protected by Hidden Villa and the Mid-Peninsula Regional Open Space District.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Below the confluences of the "three forks", Adobe Creek is joined by three seasonal creeks in Los Altos Hills.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The first is 1.3-mile-long (2.1 km) **Moody Creek** (known locally as **Silver Creek**) and named for George Washington Moody (1824–1909), a farmer who lived along the stream.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] His home was located on Moody Creek (which flows down along Central Drive and then Moody Court to its confluence with Adobe Creek).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The next Adobe Creek tributary is 2.0-mile-long (3.2 km) **Purisima Creek** (historically known as **Purissima Creek** and originating between Altamont Road and Dezahara Way and joining Adobe Creek at Deepwater Lane and Bay Tree Lane) and **Robleda Creek** (along Robleda Road) in Los Altos Hills.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Thence, Adobe Creek departs mountainous and hilly terrain and enters the valley floor to descend through Los Altos, Mountain View, and Palo Alto.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The creek's course runs 11 miles (18 km).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Further downstream, the Palo Alto/Los Altos bike path traverses the creek, running along the Hetch Hetchy Aqueduct right of way.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Several sections of Adobe Creek have been re-aligned, including the trapezoidal concrete drainage channel between El Camino Real and U.S.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Highway 101 (the portion between Alma Street and El Camino Real was constructed by the SCVWD in 1959).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Roscoe installed a flood gate at 12243 Tepa Way which can redirect the flows into the old Adobe Creek channel.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] In 1975, an 8-foot pipe bypass intended to prevent flooding of properties along Adobe Creek was constructed starting near the intersection of Moody and El Monte Roads (on the Foothill College Campus) going upstream approximately 2,200 feet, ending just upstream of Tepa Way.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The original creek channel is now a secondary water "bypass channel" that bears high winter water flows from Adobe Creek and meanders through several properties in the Adobe Lane subdivision before passing under Moody Road and returning to the mainstem at the southeast corner of Foothill College.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Before passing under Highway 101, Adobe Creek is joined by Barron Creek just upstream of Highway 101.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Barron Creek was alternatively known as **Dry Creek**, and appears as a tributary of Adobe Creek in the 1862 Allardt Map, although in the 1899 Topo Map it was tributary to Matadero Creek, and was much later diverted back to Adobe Creek.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Barron Creek has been greatly modified for flood control purposes; the creek bed downstream from El Camino Real is a concrete trapezoidal channel.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] After passing under Highway 101, Adobe Creek enters the Palo Alto Flood Basin just west of a levee at the end of San Antonio Road.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] This levee separates Charleston Slough on the east from Mayfield Slough on the west and is also the eastern border of the Palo Alto Baylands.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The Flood Basin is maintained a couple feet below sea level in order to absorb floodwaters from Adobe Creek and Matadero Creek.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] By lowering the basin, what was once tidal saltwater marsh is now predominantly freshwater marsh.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Adobe Creek is joined by Matadero Creek at the north end of Mayfield Slough, where it historically joined with San Francisquito Creek before the latter was diverted north.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Mayfield Slough has a tidal gate through which fresh water passes to San Francisco Bay, and some salt water is permitted to return to Mayfield Slough when the tides are higher.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] In the 1800s the Baylands marshes ended between Alma and El Camino Real in Palo Alto, which explains why historical maps show area creeks appearing to terminate before they reach the Bay.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Duck-hunting blinds were common in the nineteenth century along what is now Middlefield Road.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The 1862 Allardt map shows Adobe Creek, then **Yeguas Creek**, having dual termini – one in the Baylands Marsh and the other to San Francisquito Creek just before entering San Francisco Bay.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The creek flows through **Redwood Grove**, a 5.9-acre (24,000 m2) nature preserve off University Avenue in Los Altos purchased by the city in 1974.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] In October, 2009 Los Altos contracted with Acterra to remove non-native plants and revitalize the redwood, oak woodland, riparian and grassland ecosystems by installing native plants, improving soil conditions, and creating habitat for wildlife such as bird houses and native bee boxes.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The coast redwoods (*Sequoia sempervirens*) were transplanted by the Halsey family from a location on Summit Road in the Santa Cruz Mountains and replaced the native willows.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] At Manresa Bridge at the east edge of Redwood Grove one can see the native red willow (*Salix laevigata*) and arroyo willow (*Salix lasiolepis*) trees.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The historic Halsey House, built in the late 1920s by Theodore and Emma Halsey, is a good example of Spanish Revival architecture.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The city designated Halsey House a local landmark in 1981 and until recently it housed the Florence Fava collection of Coastanoan or Ohlone Indian artifacts from a creekside archeological excavation in Los Altos Hills (now moved to the Los Altos History House).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] On June 16, 2010, the Los Altos City Council finalized the purchase of 10,000 square feet (930 m2) of creekside property from Delbert and Marlene Beumer, who wanted to provide a safe pathway connecting **Shoup Park** and **Redwood Grove**.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Riparian vegetation was described in the 1989 *Adobe Creek Restoration Plan*.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Steelhead trout (*Oncorhynchus mykiss*) occurred historically in Adobe Creek.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The earliest report touted the trout in the Sportsman's Gazetteer in 1877.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] This very early report makes rumors that Adobe Creek's trout were introduced extremely unlikely since the first trout hatcheries in California did not propagate any trout until the 1870s, and much of their production was shipped to hatcheries out of state.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] A physical specimen was collected in 1893 by Wilbur Wilson Thoburn, Stanford University Professor of Bionomics, and is preserved in the California Academy of Sciences collection.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] In 1898 John Otterbein Snyder, ichthyologist and Stanford Professor of Zoology, also collected steelhead trout specimens in **San Antonio Creek** (now Adobe Creek).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] A 1909 land office brochure promoted Los Altos for its "never-failing mountain trout stream, trout caught a few feet from kitchen doors".
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The reaches upstream from Hidden Villa have been judged excellent trout spawning habitat.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] A 27-inch steelhead trout (see main photo) caught by boys in June, 1956 about two blocks from Van Buren Avenue (now Van Buren Street) is the last historical record of this salmonid ascending Adobe Creek to spawn upstream of El Camino Real.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Steelhead spawning runs were partially blocked by construction of the tidal gate in the Palo Alto Flood Basin at the mouth of Adobe Creek in 1957.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] In 1959, steelhead trout spawning runs were completely blocked by another flood control project on Adobe Creek, when the Santa Clara Valley Water District transformed the natural stream channel into a concrete trapezoidal chute with eight foot drop and dysfunctional fish ladder below El Camino Real.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The 2.4 miles (3.9 km) long concrete trapezoidal channel structure from El Camino Real northward to Highway 101 stops fish with thin sheets of rapid horizontal flow during winter.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Today there are additional upstream barriers to fish passage, including drop structures below the culverts under Interstate 280 and Foothill Expressway.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Additional barriers occur at the O'Keefe Lane and Hidden Villa bridges, and the creek suffers from significant bank erosion, failing channel stabilization structures, and sedimentation.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Finally, the trash rack at the tidal gate at the mouth of Mayfield Slough in the Palo Alto Flood Basin continues as an intermittent complete barrier to fish passage when it is closed.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Four species of native fishes have been collected from Adobe Creek in 2011: California roach (*Lavinia symmetricus*), Sacramento sucker (*Catostomus occidentalis occidentalis*), three-spined stickleback (*Gasterosteus aculeatus*), and prickly sculpin (*Cottus asper*).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Leidy reported the fish still inhabiting the Adobe Creek's lowest reach in 2007 – native California roach, Sacramento sucker, three-spined stickleback, and non-native common carp (*Cyprinus carpio*), rainwater killifish (*Lucania parva*), and western mosquitofish (*Gambusia affinis*).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The Palo Alto Flood Basin was constructed in 1956 in order to prevent a repeat of the floods of 1955, when a high tide prevented the escape of heavy runoff from Matadero, Adobe, and Barron Creeks into the San Francisco Bay.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The trapped runoff waters overflowed upstream creek banks and caused severe flooding in Palo Alto.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] In order to control the flow of water into the flood basin, a tidegate was placed at the confluence of Adobe Creek, Matadero Creek, and the San Francisco Bay, so that the flood basin could be maintained at approximately 2 feet below sea level, creating room to absorb floodwaters.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The tidegate consists of several weirs and one operator-controlled sluice gate that enables tidal flows into the basin in order to improve water quality and for mosquito control.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Three agencies oversee the tidegates: Santa Clara Valley Water District, City of Palo Alto, and Santa Clara County Vector Control.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Because the trash grate and weirs separate the mouth of the flood basin from the San Francisco Bay estuary, large fish cannot swim freely between the Bay and the basin, unless the sluice gate is open.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] In addition, the tidegates are set to reduce tidal inflows into the basin, so that the basin is mostly freshwater.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] After a rainstorm the tidegate is kept closed, however this is precisely when steelhead trout in-migrations should occur.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] In 2002 a small opening was cut in the trash grate on the tidal gate to permit fish passage but local fisherman in the Flood Basin no longer report catching steelhead trout in recent years.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] From November 16 to 20, 2002, approximately 100 striped bass (*Morone saxatilis*), 5 bat rays (*Myliobatis californica*) and 2 leopard sharks (*Triakis semifasciata*) were found dead in the Flood Control Basin in both Adobe and Matadero Creeks within one mile of the tidegate.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The fishkill was attributed to the first large rainstorm washing a large amount of leaf litter into the basin, leading to eutrophication and low dissolved oxygen.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] This is supported by the fact that the dead fish were all large (requiring more oxygen) at 2 to 4 feet long and the mouths and gills of the bass were fully extended open.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The San Francisco Bay Trail, which passes in a loop around both sides of the Palo Alto Flood Basin is known as the Adobe Creek Loop Trail and is easily accessed from a parking lot at the northern terminus of San Antonio Road, just north of U.S.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] A scenic, easy walking or mountain biking trail, it also provides outstanding birdwatching and in winter is known for its flock of American white pelicans (*Pelecanus erythrorhynchos*).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The Adobe Creek Loop Trail begins by heading north along the levee between Adobe Creek and the Charleston Slough out to the confluence of Adobe Creek and Matadero Creek.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] As one heads north on the levee, Charleston Slough is on the right and Adobe Creek is on the left.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The Charleston Slough is a rich salt marsh and littoral zone, providing feeding areas for a variety of shorebirds and other estuarine wildlife.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] At low tide Charleston Slough looks like a salt pond, like the Cargill salt ponds to the east of it, but it is open to tidal flow.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Pumps and gates regulate the flow through the slough.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Water from the slough gets pumped into Shoreline Lake, which then drains into Permanente Creek.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The slough was named after George Charleston, who came from Scotland in 1852 and purchased 160 acres (0.65 km2) of marshland in this area.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Charleston Road and Charleston Court also bear his name.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Continuing north, the wide, curving Loop Trail eventually touches San Francisco Bay itself and curves to the west, crossing over the tidal gate of Mayfield Slough and enters the Palo Alto Baylands Nature Preserve.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The sailing station boat launching dock is visible on the opposite shore of the channel at the mouth of the former Palo Alto Yacht Harbor.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Baylands Nature Preserve surrounds what used to be the Palo Alto Yacht Harbor, now a silted-in mud flat and marsh which provides excellent birding.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The Adobe Creek Loop Trail then heads back southwest with Matadero Creek on the left and Byxbee Park (former landfill) on the right, eventually connecting to the Bay Trail at East Bayshore Road.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Heading east along East Bayshore Road, turn immediately left after crossing over Adobe Creek to return on the Bay Trail to the San Antonio Road parking lot.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Many locals enjoy the natural setting of a short walk through Redwood Grove, of which portions are on an elevated wooden boardwalk.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] In 1986 the city of Los Altos was granted an open space easement on the south bank of Adobe Creek and developed a trail from the south end of Redwood Grove to the Manresa Lane Bridge.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Hidden Villa is the starting point for the relatively gentle Adobe Creek Trail, an easy 0.8 miles (1.3 km) hike upstream (one-way) along a cool, wooded canyon culminating at a plaque commemorating the founding of the Loma Prieta Chapter of the Sierra Club.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] Two routes connect Hidden Villa to the Black Mountain Trail at Ewing Hill at 1,200 feet (370 m) of elevation, the Hostel Trail (1.3 miles) or the Adobe Creek Trail (0.8 mile) connecting to the Ewing Trail (0.3 miles).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/adobe-creek-santa-clara-county-california] The Black Mountain Trail then continues up a strenuous 3 miles (4.8 km) to the 2,800-foot (850 m) summit of Black Mountain.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Studies of business growth and performance in farming have found that successful agricultural businesses are cost-efficient internally and operate in favourable economic, political, and physical-organic environments.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] They are able to expand and make profits, improve the productivity of land, labor, and capital, and keep their costs down to ensure market price competitiveness.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] It encompasses a broader spectrum through the agribusiness system which includes input supplies, value-addition, marketing, entrepreneurship, microfinancing, and agricultural extension.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] In some countries like the Philippines, creation and management of agribusiness enterprises require consultation with registered agriculturists above a certain level of operations, capitalization, land area, or number of animals in the farm.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] The word "agribusiness" is a portmanteau of the words *agriculture* and *business.* The earliest known use of the word was in the Volume 155 of the Canadian Almanac & Directory published in 1847.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Their book argued against the New Deal programs of then U.S.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] President Franklin Roosevelt as it led to the increase in agricultural prices.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Davis and Goldberg favored corporate-driven agriculture or large-scale farming to revolutionize the agriculture sector, lessening the dependency on state power and politics.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] They explained in the book that vertically integrated firms within the agricultural value chains have the ability to control prices and where they are distributed.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Goldberg then assisted in the establishment of the first undergraduate program in agribusiness in 1966 at the UP College of Agriculture in Los Baños, Philippines as Bachelor of Science in Agriculture major in Agribusiness.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] The program was initially a joint undertaking with the UP College of Business Administration in Diliman, Quezon City until 1975.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Drilon of the University of the Philippines then published the book "*Agribusiness Management Resource Materials*" (1971) which would be the foundation of current agribusiness programs around the world.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] In 1973, Drilon and Goldberg further expanded the concept of agribusiness to include support organizations such as governments, research institutions, schools, financial institutions, and cooperatives within the integrated Agribusiness System.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Shultz II (2005) of Loyola University Chicago reframed the definition of agribusiness to emphasize its lack of focus on farm production but towards market centricity and innovative approach to serve consumers worldwide.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Boland defined the unique economic characteristics of agribusiness supply chains from industrial manufacturing and service supply chains.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] In 2017, noting the rise of genetic engineering and biotechnology in agriculture, Goldberg further expanded the definition of agribusiness which covers all the interdependent aspects of the food system including medicine, nutrition, and health.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] He also emphasized the responsibility of agribusiness to be environmentally and socially conscious towards sustainability.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Some agribusinesses have adopted the triple bottom line framework such as aligning for fair trade, organic, good agricultural practices, and B-corporation certifications towards the concept of social entrepreneurship.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] The term value chain was first popularized in a book published in 1985 by Michael Porter, who used it to illustrate how companies could achieve what he called “competitive advantage” by adding value within their organization.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Subsequently, the term was adopted for agricultural development purposes and has now become very much in vogue among those working in this field, with most bilateral and multilateral aid organisations using it to guide their development interventions.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] At the heart of the agricultural value chain concept is the idea of actors connected along a chain producing and delivering goods to consumers through a sequence of activities.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] However, this “vertical” chain cannot function in isolation and an important aspect of the value chain approach is that it also considers “horizontal” impacts on the chain, such as input and finance provision, extension support and the general enabling environment.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] The approach has been found useful, particularly by donors, in that it has resulted in a consideration of all those factors impacting on the ability of farmers to access markets profitably, leading to a broader range of chain interventions.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] It is used both for upgrading existing chains and for donors to identify market opportunities for small farmers.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] An agricultural supply store or agrocenter is an agriculturally-oriented shop where one sells agricultural supplies — inputs required for agricultural production such as pesticides, feed and fertilizers .
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Sometimes these stores are organized as cooperatives, where store customers aggregate their resources to purchase agricultural inputs.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Agricultural supply and the stores that provide it are part of the larger Agribusiness industry.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] A farmworker or farmhand, is someone employed for labor in agriculture.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] In labor law, the term "farmworker" is sometimes used more narrowly, applying only to a hired worker involved in agricultural production, including harvesting.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Agricultural work varies widely depending on context, degree of mechanization and crop.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Low wages for farmworkers have been associated with farmworker shortages and delayed adoption of agricultural technology.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Agricultural labor is often affected by the human health impacts of environmental issues related to agriculture, such as health effects of pesticides or exposure to other health challenges such as valley fever.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] To address these environmental concerns and marginal working conditions, many labor rights, economic justice and environmental justice movements have been organized or supported by farmworkers.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Irrigation in agriculture is the practice of applying controlled amounts of water to land to help grow crops, landscape plants, and lawns.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Irrigation has been a key aspect of agriculture for over 5,000 years and has been developed by many cultures worldwide.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Irrigation helps to grow crops, maintain landscapes, and revegetate disturbed soils in dry areas and during times of below-average rainfall.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] In addition to these uses, irrigation is also employed to protect crops from frost, suppress weed growth in grain fields, and prevent soil consolidation.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] It is also used to cool livestock, reduce dust, dispose of sewage, and support mining operations.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Drainage, which involves the removal of surface and sub-surface water from a given location, is often studied in conjunction with irrigation.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Irrigation and drainage improvements are not necessarily mutually exclusive.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Often both may be required together to assure sustained high-level production of crops.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] For a discussion of the role of drainage practices in agriculture .
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Several irrigation methods differ in how water is supplied to plants.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Surface irrigation, also known as gravity irrigation, is the oldest form of irrigation and has been in use for thousands of years.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] In sprinkler irrigation, water is piped to one or more central locations within the field and distributed by overhead high-pressure water devices.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Micro-irrigation is a system that distributes water under low pressure through a piped network and applies it as a small discharge to each plant.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Micro-irrigation uses less pressure and water flow than sprinkler irrigation.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Drip irrigation delivers water directly to the root zone of plants.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Subirrigation has been used in field crops in areas with high water tables for many years.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] It involves artificially raising the water table to moisten the soil below the root zone of plants.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Irrigation water can come from groundwater (extracted from springs or by using wells), from surface water (withdrawn from rivers, lakes or reservoirs) or from non-conventional sources like treated wastewater, desalinated water, drainage water, or fog collection.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Irrigation can be supplementary to rainfall, which is common in many parts of the world as rainfed agriculture, or it can be full irrigation, where crops rarely rely on any contribution from rainfall.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Full irrigation is less common and occurs only in arid landscapes with very low rainfall or when crops are grown in semi-arid areas outside the rainy season.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] The environmental effects of irrigation relate to the changes in quantity and quality of soil and water as a result of irrigation and the subsequent effects on natural and social conditions in river basins and downstream of an irrigation scheme.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] The effects stem from altered hydrological conditions resulting from the installation and operation of the irrigation scheme.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Amongst these problems is the depletion of underground aquifers through overdrafting.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Soil can be over-irrigated due to poor distribution uniformity or management wastes water, chemicals, and may lead to water pollution.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Over-irrigation can cause deep drainage from rising water tables, which can lead to irrigation salinity problems, requiring watertable control through some form of subsurface land drainage.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Seed companies produce and sell seeds for flowers, fruits and vegetables to commercial growers and amateur gardeners.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] The production of seed is a multibillion-dollar global business, which uses growing facilities and growing locations worldwide.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] While most of the seed is produced by large specialist growers, large amounts are also produced by small growers who produce only one to a few crop types.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] The larger companies supply seed both to commercial resellers and wholesalers.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] The resellers and wholesalers sell to vegetable and fruit growers, and to companies who package seed into packets and sell them on to the amateur gardener.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Most seed companies or resellers that sell to retail produce a catalog, for seed to be sown the following spring, that is generally published during early winter.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] These catalogs are eagerly awaited by the amateur gardener, as during winter months there is little that can be done in the garden so this time can be spent planning the following year’s gardening.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] The largest collection of nursery and seed trade catalogs in the U.S. is held at the National Agricultural Library where the earliest catalogs date from the late 18th century, with most published from the 1890s to the present.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Seed companies produce a huge range of seeds from highly developed F1 hybrids to open pollinated wild species.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] They have extensive research facilities to produce plants with genetic materials that result in improved uniformity and appeal.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] These qualities might include disease resistance, higher yields, dwarf habit and vibrant or new colors.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] These improvements are often closely guarded to protect them from being utilized by other producers, thus plant cultivars are often sold under the company's own name and protected by international laws from being grown for seed production by others.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Along with the growth in the allotment movement, and the increasing popularity of gardening, there have emerged many small independent seed companies.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Many of these are active in seed conservation and encouraging diversity.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] They often offer organic and open pollinated varieties of seeds as opposed to hybrids.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Many of these varieties are heirloom varieties.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] The use of old varieties maintains diversity in the horticultural gene pool.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] It may be more appropriate for amateur gardeners to use older (heirloom) varieties as the modern seed types are often the same as those grown by commercial producers, and so characteristics which are useful to them (e.g. vegetables ripening at the same time) may be unsuited to home growing.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] A fertilizer or fertiliser is any material of natural or synthetic origin that is applied to soil or to plant tissues to supply plant nutrients.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Fertilizers may be distinct from liming materials or other non-nutrient soil amendments.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Many sources of fertilizer exist, both natural and industrially produced.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] For most modern agricultural practices, fertilization focuses on three main macronutrients: nitrogen (N), phosphorus (P), and potassium (K) with occasional addition of supplements like rock flour for micronutrients.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Farmers apply these fertilizers in a variety of ways: through dry or pelletized or liquid application processes, using large agricultural equipment, or hand-tool methods.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Historically, fertilization came from natural or organic sources: compost, animal manure, human manure, harvested minerals, crop rotations, and byproducts of human-nature industries (e.g. fish processing waste, or bloodmeal from animal slaughter).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] However, starting in the 19th century, after innovations in plant nutrition following Justus von Liebig's discoveries, an agricultural industry developed around synthetically created agrochemical fertilizers.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] This transition was important in transforming the global food system towards larger-scale industrial agriculture with large crop yields in monocultures.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] The invention of Haber process for producing ammonia for nitrogen in the 20th century combined with amplified chemical production capacity created during World War II led to a boom in using nitrogen fertilizers.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] In the latter half of the 20th century, increased use of nitrogen fertilizers (800% increase between 1961 and 2019) has been a crucial component of the increased productivity of conventional food systems as part of the so-called "Green Revolution".
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Fertilizers, especially when applied excessively, can have environmental consequences such as water pollution and eutrophication due to nutrient runoff.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Additionally, the chemical process for creating the fertilizers results in byproducts, including carbon and other emissions.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] In some cases contamination and pollution of soil result by accumulation of heavy metals contained in some fertilizers collected through mining.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Sustainable agricultural practices, such as reduced tillage and planting buffer strips, can minimize these adverse environmental effects.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] A farm (also called an agricultural holding) is an area of land that is devoted primarily to agricultural processes with the primary objective of producing food and other crops; it is the basic facility in food production.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] The name is used for specialized units such as arable farms, vegetable farms, fruit farms, dairy, pig and poultry farms, and land used for the production of natural fiber, biofuel, and other biobased products.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] It includes ranches, feedlots, orchards, plantations and estates, smallholdings, and hobby farms, and includes the farmhouse and agricultural buildings as well as the land.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] In modern times, the term has been extended to include such industrial operations as wind farms and fish farms, both of which can operate on land or at sea.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] There are about 570 million farms in the world, most of which are small and family-operated.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Small farms with a land area of fewer than 2 hectares operate on about 12% of the world's agricultural land, and family farms comprise about 75% of the world's agricultural land.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Modern farms in developed countries are highly mechanized.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] In the United States, livestock may be raised on rangeland and finished in feedlots, and the mechanization of crop production has brought about a great decrease in the number of agricultural workers needed.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] In Europe, traditional family farms are giving way to larger production units.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] In Australia, some farms are very large because the land is unable to support a high stocking density of livestock because of climatic conditions.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] In less developed countries, small farms are the norm, and the majority of rural residents are subsistence farmers, feeding their families and selling any surplus products in the local market.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] An agricultural engineer is an engineer with an agriculture background.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Agricultural engineers make the engineering designs and plans in an agricultural project, usually in partnership with an agriculturist who is more proficient in farming and agricultural science.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Primary food processing turns agricultural products, such as raw wheat kernels or livestock, into something that can eventually be eaten.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] This category includes ingredients that are produced by ancient processes such as drying, threshing, winnowing and milling grain, shelling nuts, and butchering animals for meat.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] It also includes deboning and cutting meat, freezing and smoking fish and meat, extracting and filtering oils, canning food, preserving food through food irradiation, and candling eggs, as well as homogenizing and pasteurizing milk.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Contamination and spoilage problems in primary food processing can lead to significant public health threats, as the resulting foods are used so widely.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] However, many forms of processing contribute to improved food safety and longer shelf life before the food spoils.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Commercial food processing uses control systems such as hazard analysis and critical control points (HACCP) and failure mode and effects analysis (FMEA) to reduce the risk of harm.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Secondary food processing is the everyday process of creating food from ingredients that are ready to use.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Baking bread, regardless of whether it is made at home, in a small bakery, or in a large factory, is an example of secondary food processing.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Fermenting fish and making wine, beer, and other alcoholic products are traditional forms of secondary food processing.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Sausages are a common form of secondary processed meat, formed by comminution (grinding) of meat that has already undergone primary processing.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Most of the secondary food processing methods known to humankind are commonly described as cooking methods.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Agricultural marketing covers the services involved in moving an agricultural product from the farm to the consumer.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] These services involve the planning, organizing, directing and handling of agricultural produce in such a way as to satisfy farmers, intermediaries and consumers.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Numerous interconnected activities are involved in doing this, such as planning production, growing and harvesting, grading, packing and packaging, transport, storage, agro- and food processing, provision of market information, distribution, advertising and sale.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Effectively, the term encompasses the entire range of supply chain operations for agricultural products, whether conducted through *ad hoc* sales or through a more integrated chain, such as one involving contract farming.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] A farmers' market (or farmers market according to the AP stylebook, also farmer's market in the Cambridge Dictionary) is a physical retail marketplace intended to sell foods directly by farmers to consumers.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Farmers' markets may be indoors or outdoors and typically consist of booths, tables or stands where farmers sell their produce, live animals and plants, and sometimes prepared foods and beverages.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Farmers' markets exist in many countries worldwide and reflect the local culture and economy.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] The size of the market may be just a few stalls or it may be as large as several city blocks.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Due to their nature, they tend to be less rigidly regulated than retail produce shops.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] They are distinguished from public markets, which are generally housed in permanent structures, open year-round, and offer a variety of non-farmer/non-producer vendors, packaged foods and non-food products.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Agricultural extension is the application of scientific research and new knowledge to agricultural practices through farmer education.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] The field of 'extension' now encompasses a wider range of communication and learning activities organized for rural people by educators from different disciplines, including agriculture, agricultural marketing, health, and business studies.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Extension practitioners can be found throughout the world, usually working for government agencies.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] They are represented by several professional organizations, networks and extension journals.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Agricultural extension agencies in developing countries receive large amounts of support from international development organizations such as the World Bank and the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] An agricultural cooperative, also known as a farmers' co-op, is a producer cooperative in which farmers pool their resources in certain areas of activities.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Agricultural production cooperatives include collective farms in former socialist countries, the kibbutzim in Israel, collectively-governed community shared agriculture, Longo Maï cooperatives in Costa Rica, France, and some other countries, CPAs in Cuba, and Nicaraguan production cooperatives.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] In Southeast Asian developing countries such as Vietnam, agricultural cooperatives remain to play an important role in economic and social activities in rural areas, although they have relied mainly on government subsidies .
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Notable examples of agricultural cooperatives include Dairy Farmers Of America, the largest dairy company in the US, Amul, the largest food product marketing organization in India, and Zen-Noah, a federation of agricultural cooperatives that handles 70% of the sales of chemical fertilizers in Japan.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Agricultural cooperatives are owned and democratically controlled by their members.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] The governance structure can vary between the different types, but in general members elect representatives to a board of directors and contribute to organizational decision making through a democratic voting process.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] The Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) is a specialized agency of the United Nations that leads international efforts to defeat hunger and improve nutrition and food security.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Its Latin motto, *fiat panis*, translates to "let there be bread".
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] It was founded on 16 October 1945 in Quebec City, Canada.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] The FAO comprises 194 members, including 193 countries and one member organization, the European Union (EU).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Its headquarters is in Rome, Italy, and it maintains regional and field offices worldwide, operating in over 130 countries.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] It helps governments and development agencies coordinate their activities to improve and develop agriculture, forestry, fisheries, and land and water resources.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] It also conducts research, provides technical assistance to projects, operates educational and training programs, and collects agricultural output, production, and development data.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] The FAO is governed by a biennial conference representing each member country and the EU, which elects a 49-member executive council.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] of China, serves as the chief administrative officer.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Various committees govern matters such as finance, programs, agriculture, and fisheries.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Obverse: Young woman with braid facing left.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Reverse: Cow nursing calf, face value & date.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] An agriculturist, agriculturalist, agrologist, or agronomist (abbreviated as agr.) is a professional in the science, practice, and management of agriculture and agribusiness.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] It is a regulated profession in Canada, Pakistan, India, Japan, the Philippines, the United States, and the European Union.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Other names used to designate the profession include agricultural scientist, agricultural manager, agricultural planner, agriculture researcher, or agriculture policy maker.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] The primary role of agriculturists are in leading agricultural projects and programs, usually in agribusiness planning or research for the benefit of farms, food, and agribusiness-related organizations.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Agriculturists usually are designated in the government as public agriculturists serving as agriculture policymakers or technical advisors for policy making.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Preparation of technical engineering designs and construction for agriculture meanwhile are reserved for agricultural engineers.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Agriculturists may pursue environmental planning and focus on agricultural and rural planning.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Studies of agribusiness often come from the academic fields of agricultural economics and management studies, sometimes called agribusiness management.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] To promote more development of food economies, many government agencies support the research and publication of economic studies and reports exploring agribusiness and agribusiness practices.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Some of these studies are on foods produced for export and are derived from agencies focused on food exports.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] These agencies include the Foreign Agricultural Service (FAS) of the U.S.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Department of Agriculture, Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada (AAFC), Austrade, and New Zealand Trade and Enterprise (NZTE).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] The Federation of International Trade Associations publishes studies and reports by FAS and AAFC, as well as other non-governmental organizations on its website.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] In their book *A Concept of Agribusiness*, Ray Goldberg and John Davis provided a rigorous economic framework for the field.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] They traced a complex value-added chain that begins with the farmer's purchase of seed and livestock and ends with a product fit for the consumer's table.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] Agribusiness boundary expansion is driven by a variety of transaction costs.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] As concern over global warming intensifies, biofuels derived from crops are gaining increased public and scientific attention.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] This is driven by factors such as oil price spikes, the need for increased energy security, concern over greenhouse gas emissions from fossil fuels, and support from government subsidies.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/agribusiness] In Europe and in the US, increased research and production of biofuels have been mandated by law.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] This article addresses various **criticisms of Cargill**, a privately held agribusiness multinational giant with operations in 70 countries and its headquarters in Minneapolis, Minnesota, in the United States.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Cargill Inc has been owned by the Cargill family for 154 years.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] It is the largest privately owned corporation in the United States, with an annual revenue of $113.5 billion in 2019.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Concerns have been raised about Cargill's environmental and human rights record in a number of industries and countries by the Roundtable on Sustainable Palm Oil (RSPO) and other organizations since at least the early 2000s.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] As a highly influential company, Cargill has been called upon to reduce its negative industrial, environmental, and societal impacts, in hopes that it would set global precedents for similar businesses.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Cargill is one of four "trading giants" known as the ABCD group— ADM, Bunge, Cargill, and Dreyfus that controls over fifty percent of the processing capacity in soybeans in the Brazilian Cerrado, and have heavily invested in storage and ports.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] As the Brazilian Cerrado has been transformed into the world's "soy basket" Greenpeace, local indigenous groups and other environmental groups say that Cargill has contributed to deforestation of the Amazon forest.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Greenpeace protests contributed to Cargill's port being shut down from 2007 to 2012.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Cargill Inc is owned by five generations of the Cargill family.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Its annual revenue in fiscal year 2019 was $113.5 billion.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Cargill is a member of Roundtable on Sustainable Palm Oil (RSPO) (2004–) and Soft Commodities Forum (SCF) (2019–) which was convened by the World Business Council for Sustainable Development (WBCSD).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Concerns have been raised about Cargill's environmental record in a number of industries and countries by the Roundtable on Sustainable Palm Oil (RSPO) and other organizations since at least the early 2000s.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Cargill has been called a "cartel" in a 2016 book entitled *The Political Economy of Agricultural Booms: Managing Soybean Production in Argentina, Brazil, and Paraguay*.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Cargill has corporate social responsibility policies and industry commitments to produce palm oil sustainably.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] In 2004, Cargill became a certified member of the RSPO, which sets standards for palm oil production.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Certified member companies are expected to voluntarily comply with RSPO principles, criteria, and adhere to best practices.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] According to a 2004 Friends of the Earth article, at that time, Cargill owned five oil palm plantations, through their oil palm arm CTP Holdings, in Indonesia and Papua New Guinea.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] In 2004, Cargill was the largest US importer of palm oil, sourcing the oil from at least 26 producers and buying roughly 11% of Indonesia's total oil palm output.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] By 2006, there had been hundreds of cases of social conflict documented at Cargill's oil palm plantations by NGOs, government, and Indonesia's National Human Rights Court.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] A 2006 *Jakarta Post* article said that Cargill purchased palm oil from many more 'worst-of-the-worst' rainforest destroyers—including Wilmar International, Sinar Mas, and Duta Palma—all of whom violate Indonesian law by burning rainforests.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] A 2007 FAO report said that oil palm plantations were driving the destruction of tropical rainforests around the globe.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Indonesia—which had the world's highest rate of deforestation, with, on average, 20 square miles (52 km2) of rainforest destroyed everyday—was ground zero for oil palm expansion, and produced more than 45 percent of the world's palm oil.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Palm oil is a globally traded commodity used in a wide range of consumer products, including packaged foods, cosmetics, and cleaning supplies, and as a feedstock for biofuels.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Produced in the world's tropics on industrial monoculture plantations, oil palm has severe and widespread negative impacts on the environment and local people.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] It was reported at the 2008 Asian Studies Association of Australia, that local communities had lost their ancestral forests and farmland to Cargill's oil palm plantations.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] These communities were not properly compensated for their lands, nor did they give their free, prior, and informed consent for the conversion of their lands to industrial monoculture.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] According to the Rainforest Action Network, by 2009, 83,000 hectares of Cargill's five directly owned oil palm plantations had been carved out of lowland rainforests, causing massive deforestation.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] At that time, Cargill was actively clearing forest in Borneo at their PT Harapan Sawit Lestari plantation without an environmental impact assessment, which was required by Indonesian law.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] The RSPO 2007 report said that at Cargill's three oil palm plantations in Papua New Guinea (PNG), formally independent farmers are being converted into de facto bonded laborers through Cargill's use of complex debt schemes and unfulfilled promises of new roads, schools, and hospitals.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Covering rugged and isolated terrain, Cargill's own management had acknowledged their inability to prevent the use of child labor on their PNG plantations.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Cargill began operating palm oil plantations in the mid-1990s in South Sumatra.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] By 2019, Cargill employed 6,000 women and 13,000 men in Southeast Asia.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] By 2012, Cargill was one of a group of large multinational companies, along with ADM, Bunge, Dreyfus (referred to as the ABCD) group, that controlled over fifty percent of the processing capacity in soybeans, and had heavily invested in storage and ports.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] In 2003, Cargill completed a port for processing soya in Santarém "on the northern end of highway BR-163" in the Amazon region of Brazil which reduced transportation costs.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] The port reduced the cost of transport and increased access to processing facilities, which dramatically increased incentives to produce more soya in the "heavily forested areas nearby".
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] As local farmers cleared land in the rain forest for soya crops, in late 2003, Greenpeace launched a campaign to protest Cargill's new port.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Although Cargill had complied with state legislation, they had failed to comply with a federal law requiring an Environmental Impact Statement.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] In February 2006, the federal courts in Brazil gave Cargill six months to complete an environmental assessment (EA), different from an Environmental Impact Statement (EIS).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] This ruling came as part of a broader popular backlash against the port.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] The local community had supported the port because of the promise of new jobs.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Opinions changes as the jobs were not forthcoming.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] In July 2006, federal prosecutor Felicia Pontes Jr. suggested they were close to shutting down the port.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] The port was shut down in 2007 by the Brazilian Environmental Agency.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Greenpeace released a report in April 2006, criticising Cargill for its alleged role in deforestation of the Amazon.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] The report said that Cargill was the dominant company that exposed deforestation to the indigenous tribes, making them vulnerable for the loss of their lands.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] The report also said that Cargill had slave labourers working at these soya farms 16 hours a day, seven days a week.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] The report traced animal feed made from Amazonian soy to European food retailers who bought chicken and other meat raised on the feed.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Greenpeace took its campaign to these major food retailers and quickly won agreement from McDonald's along with UK retailers Asda, Waitrose and Marks & Spencer to stop buying meat raised on Amazonian soya.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] These retailers in turn put pressure on Cargill and Archer Daniels Midland, Bunge, André Maggi Group and Dreyfus to prove their soy was not grown on recently deforested land in the Amazon.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] In July 2006, Cargill, in partnership with The Nature Conservancy (TNC), and other soy businesses, signed the Soy Moratorium agreement, through which they agreed to a two-year moratorium on the purchase of soybeans from newly deforested land.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] In 2010 Cargill submitted an Environmental Impact Assessment (EIA) for the port and it was re-opened in 2012.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] By 2015, six new ports were under consideration resulting in exponential growth.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] In June 2019, Cargill Inc admitted that the soy industry in Brazil would not meet the goal that soy companies had set in the 2000s, to "end deforestation" in Brazil by 2020.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] By July 2019, Brazil had become the world's biggest soybean exporter.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] The construction of new ports, "terminals and barge fleets" on the Amazon River by the ABCD "trading giants"—ADM, Bunge, Cargill, and Dreyfus—made the soybean industry even more competitive against that of the United States.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] June 2007 the Australian operation of Cargill was fined A$37,500 by the New South Wales Land and Environment Court after a waste water pipeline ruptured in January 2006 which flowed into a stormwater system and into the Bomen wetland.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Cargill has triggered significant controversy with its plan to build a major new housing development of as many as 32,000 people on its privately owned salt ponds in Redwood City.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] The property was originally marshland along San Francisco Bay, and became one of the first commercial salt-making locations on the Peninsula in 1901 when portions were drained and diked off from the Bay.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Immediately after World War II, the former Leslie Salt Company modernized and expanded the plant site and harvested up to 300,000 tons of salt which it shipped to industries throughout the Pacific Rim.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Leslie was purchased by Cargill in 1978, and has continued salt-making, although under more difficult business conditions, with the opening of a large competing salt works in Baja, which is owned by Mitsubishi and the Mexican government.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] In 2000, Cargill offered the property to the US Fish and Wildlife Service and the California Department of Fish and Game, but the resource agencies were unable to afford the site, although 16,500 acres were acquired from Cargill in 2003 through a combination donation/sale.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] The state courts later ruled that the property had been overvalued by the appraiser's unfounded assumption of its value for development or mitigation.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Subsequently, Cargill partnered with luxury-home builder DMB Associates of Scottsdale, Arizona, which has submitted a "50/50 Plan" to build 12,000 houses, 1 Million Sq.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Ft of commercial space, and community facilities on about half of the 1,436 acres (2.2 mi2) site, and convert the rest to wetlands, parks, lagoons, and open space on the Bayfront in Redwood City.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] The *San Francisco Chronicle*, *San Jose Mercury News* and over 150 elected officials from around the Bay Area have called the San Francisco Bay salt ponds an unacceptable site for housing, and have come out against the project.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Local environmentalist group Save The Bay has actively criticized Cargill for trying to destroy bay wetlands.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] However, others say that campaign is false advertisement as Cargill's 50/50 plan does not call for any wetland destruction or filling of the bay, only building on their property filled with only salt ponds and salt harvesting facilities.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Residents' initial efforts to preserve the salt ponds as open space were defeated by 63% of Redwood City voters in a 2008 local referendum that sought to make development difficult by amending the city charter.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Since that time, a growing coalition of over 30 environmental, business and community groups, led by Save The Bay, has continued to fight the proposed development.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] They assert that the salt ponds should be restored as part of the neighboring Don Edwards San Francisco Bay National Wildlife Refuge and not used for housing, similar to the 16,500 acres Cargill sold in 2003, which now comprise the largest tidal wetland restoration project on the West Coast.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] In August 2004, the Florida Department of Environmental Protection warned officials at the Cargill Phosphate company in Riverview, Florida, that their dike was not sturdy enough.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Reinforcements were underway, when waves churned by Hurricane Frances broke through the dike that surrounded the retention pond, spilling 65 million gallons of acidic wastewater into Tampa Bay on September 5, 2004.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Mosaic Fertilizer—the largest phosphate mining company in the world—was owned by the Cargill family until 2012, had six Florida sites and two in Louisiana.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] In 2015, the EPA had fined Mosaic about $2 billion for "improper storage and disposal of waste from the production of phosphoric and sulfuric acids, key components of fertilizers, at Mosaic's Riverview Chemical Plant, and other sites.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] The children acting as class representative plaintiffs are proceeding anonymously, as John Does, because of feared retaliation by the farm owners where they worked.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] In 2014, the San Francisco-based 9th U.S.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Circuit Court of Appeals refused to dismiss the lawsuit filed by "former victims of child slavery." because the allegations portrayed "overseas slave labor that defendants perpetuated from headquarters in the United States." In January 2016, in *Nestle Inc v.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] 15-349*, the Supreme Court agreed with the lower court that the lawsuit would not be withdrawn.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] In January 2020, Cargill and Nestle asked the Supreme Court to end the lawsuit against them in the case, which has "been moving up and down the federal court system since 2005".
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] According to the *Los Angeles Times*, the companies are "accused of aiding and abetting slave labor by giving Ivory Coast farmers financial assistance in the expectation that cocoa prices would stay low.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] According to a 2019 article in *The Washington Post*, Cargill—described as a "large commodity trader"—is one of the "leading cocoa suppliers for the chocolate industry".
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Middle men or "pisteurs" collect bags of cocoa that are trucked to Cargill's facility in Abidjan, Côte d'Ivoire.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] The article, which focused on child labor, said that even though "Mars, Nestlé and Hershey" had pledged in the early 2000s, to "stop using cocoa harvested by children", most chocolate today continues to be harvested using child labor.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] In September 2018, Cargill was seeking to expand its storage warehouse space for cocoa in Abidjan by 100,000 square meters.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] In December 2019, Cargill announced investments of $113 million in cocoa processing facilities in Ivory Coast and Ghana.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Cargill, which has had operations in the Ivory Coast since 1997 and employs 490 people there, announced in December 2019 that they would be investing $7.7 million over three years in programs in the Ivory Coast, such as the Implementation of Child Labor Monitoring and Remediation System (CLMRS).
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Cargill operates in Uzbekistan despite admissions made by two of its representatives on separate occasions that the company is concerned about the possible use of child labor in the production of its crops.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Their concerns have been public since 2005; however, Cargill has not yet taken action to investigate or correct any possible labor violations existent in their Uzbek operations.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] The Environmental Justice Foundation named Cargill as a major buyer of Uzbek cotton, which is produced widely using uncompensated workers and is implicated in human rights abuses.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Cargill claims to have no knowledge of misconduct in either case.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] In February 2018, several employees of Cargill's Dayton, Virginia, plan protested over poor health benefits and bad working conditions, and protesting over the company allegedly firing employees that organized to create a union.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] The protests lead to nine individuals being arrested for trespassing on the plant's property in protest.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] In 1970, Cargill sold 63,000 tons of seed grain to Basra, Iraq.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Although banned in many Western countries, Cargill agreed to treat the seed grain with methylmercury.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] The shipment was sprayed red to mark its danger and indicate that it was not intended for human or animal consumption but only for use in agriculture.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] Once it arrived in Iraq in early October, however, the surplus seed was given away by the government, and a number of recipients used it as food, since the only printed warnings about the poison were written in English and Spanish, as warnings to American dock workers.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] In October 2007 Cargill announced the recall of nearly 850 000 frozen beef patties produced at its packing plant in Butler, Wisconsin.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] The patties, processed between the August 9, 2007, and August 17, 2007, were suspected of being contaminated with *E. coli*.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] The beef was sold mainly at Walmart and Sam's Club stores.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] In March 2009, Cargill Australia (Wagga) had its export licence, to export meat to Japan and the United States, placed on temporary suspension by the Australian Quarantine and Inspection Service (AQIS) after *E. coli* was detected in Cargill's export containers from its Wagga Wagga plant.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] In late April 2009, AQIS lifted Cargill Australia's suspension on its export licence.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] In 2021, JBS, National Beef, Cargill, and Tyson were sued by grocers and wholesalers, which accused the four companies of working together to drive up the price of beef.
[src:criticisms-of-cargill/criticisms-of-cargill] In 2024, McDonald's Corporation sued Cargill and the same three other companies, along with their subsidiaries, for alleged price fixing.
